>      LegendMarkers -> {{None}, {Automatic, Automatic}}, 
 
>      LabelStyle -> {{FontSize -> 12}, {FontSize -> 12}}, 
 
>      LegendLayout -> Column], After, Identity]}]\
\>"], "Output",
 CellChangeTimes->{3.988986851590251*^9},
 CellLabel->" Out[6]=",ExpressionUUID->"2b16a293-df58-4b11-8564-2ae948bb134b"]
}, Open  ]]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Takeaway", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"9670b5e0-e6ab-4f6d-bdc6-a5ddc933e0c3"],

Cell["\<\
Both implementations produce identical curvature (EquivalentQ -> True), and \
the convention-independent invariants come out right: R = -20/L^2 and \
Kretschmann = 40/L^4 for AdS5. On an explicit metric the built-in array \
operators beat OGRe by about 10x, because OGRe's object system carries \
overhead that does not pay off when the components are known up front. OGRe \
is still the better tool for its own strengths -- interactive exploration, \
index gymnastics, and harder symbolic simplification -- which is exactly why \
the library keeps both and benchmarks them against each other rather than \
picking one blindly.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"67dd7869-d794-411a-bb7e-c00998cf39d7"]
}, Open  ]]
}, Open  ]]
},
